==Development==
''Miner 2049er'' was programmed by Bill Hogue of Big Five Software of Van Nuys, California.{{sfn|Boaz|1983|p=20}}<ref name="Atari50-1">{{cite video game |title=Atari 50 |developer=[[Digital Eclipse]] |publisher=[[Atari SA|Atari]] |date=November 11, 2022 |platform=Nintendo Switch |quote='''The Dawn of PCs: Miner 2049er''': Another breakout hit for the 400/800 computers, Miner 2049er was a platform game created by Bill Hogue, which he published through his company Big Five Software. The recipient of Game of the Year in the 1984 Arkie Awards, Miner 2049er was one of the best-selling computer games of the era.}}</ref>
The game was Hogue's first for Atari computers, following games he developed for [[TRS-80]] computers.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Compute!|date=November 1982|issn=0194-357X|publisher=Small System Services|title=A Seasonal Serving of ROM Cartridges for Your Atari 400/800}}</ref> His team chose to develop for the Atari system, as they felt it was the best combination of graphics and sound.<ref name="Min2049History" /> The graphics and audio in the game are credited to Curtis A. Mikolyski, Jeff Konyu, Kelly Bakst, and Hogue.{{sfn|Big Five Software||ref=manual}} It was the group's first color computer game.<ref name="Min2049History">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040202071850/http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/atari/Miner/History/history.htm|title=Miner 2049er History|accessdate=June 15, 2023|archivedate=February 2, 2004|work=Big Five Software|url=http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/atari/Miner/History/history.htm}}</ref> Hogue stated that he was obsessed with the advanced color capabilities of the Atari computers: 15 different colors on the screen at any one time.<ref name="Min2049Tech">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040223010201/http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/atari/Miner/Technical/technical.html|title=Miner 2049er Technical Information|accessdate=June 15, 2023|archivedate=February 23, 2004|work=Big Five Software|url=http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/atari/Miner/Technical/technical.html}}</ref> A black-and-white version was developed for TRS-80 computers, but it was never released.<ref name="Min2049History" /> The game was released on a 16-[[kilobyte]] [[ROM cartridge]]â€”a large amount of storage at the time, with other games for the Atari 400 and 800 computers such as ''[[Star Raiders]]'' and ''[[Missile Command]]'' requiring only 8-kilobyte ROMs.{{sfn|Hudson|1982|p=14}} The group designed their own circuit boards to store the game at this size.<ref name="Min2049History" /> The game was written in [[assembly language]] on an Atari computer.<ref name="Min2049History" /> Hogue wanted to blend together the elements he found fun from different arcade games; specifically, the climbing from ''[[Donkey Kong (arcade game)|Donkey Kong]]'' (1981) and both traversing the entire screen and enemies who can be made vulnerable from ''[[Pac-Man]]'' (1980). He recollected that "I was never very good at ''Pac-Man'', so I'm not sure why I borrowed any elements from the game."{{sfn|Grannell|2007|p=37}} The gameplay was developed first, followed later by the mining theme and narrative.{{sfn|Grannell|2007|p=37}}  Some versions of the game feature the song "[[Oh My Darling, Clementine|Clementine]]" while others do not.<ref name="Atr481200" /><ref name="atr5200" />

Mike Livesay designed the adaptations of the game for the Apple II computer and for [[Colecovision]].<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Computer Entertainer|The Video Game Update includes Computer Entertainer]]|volume=2|issue=11|date=February 1984|title=Update on Scraper Caper|page=172}}</ref> Livesay initially approached Micro Fun about adapting the game for Colecovision but was turned down by the company, which stated that they did not want third-party games. Despite this, Livesay reverse-engineered the Colecovision and developed his own kit for it based on the [[Apple II]]. Livesay eventually got Micro Fun to agree to do the Colecovision version of the game, allowing him time to make more levels for it. He later recalled that "six months later I was making $15,000 a month in royalties, which was a huge amount for a single, 24-year-old kid in the early '80s."{{sfn|Weiss|2014|p=139}}

