''Miner 2049er'' was released for Atari computers in December 1982. This version of the game sold well, with one review stating that it sold in similar quantities to the highly publicized ''[[Ultima II: The Revenge of the Enchantress|Ultima II]]''.{{sfn|MTY|1983|p=36}} In 1983, the game was released for various systems, including the Atari 2600 in May, the Atari 5200 in July, the Colecovision in August, the [[TI-99/4A]] for October, and the [[IBM PC]] by November.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update|volume=2|issue=2|date=June 1983|title=Availability Update|page=48}}</ref><ref name="AvailUpAug83">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update includes Computer Entertainer|volume=2|issue=5|date=August 1983|title=Availability Update|page=80}}</ref><ref name="AvailUpSep83">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update includes Computer Entertainer|volume=2|issue=6|date=September 1983|title=Availability Update|page=96}}</ref><ref name="InBrief">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update includes Computer Entertainer|volume=2|issue=8|date=November 1983|title=In Brief...|page=119}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update includes Computer Entertainer|volume=2|issue=8|date=November 1983|title=Availability Guide|page=128}}</ref> The game was the first independently produced game released for the Atari 5200 and the [[ColecoVision]].<ref name="Atr481200">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update|volume=2|issue=2|date=June 1983|title=Critically Speaking..Atari 4/8/1200|page=62}}</ref><ref name="atr5200">{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update|volume=2|issue=2|date=June 1983|title=Critically Speaking..Atari 5200-Compatible|page=39}}</ref> The game would be released in Japan for systems like the [[Super Cassette Vision]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/atari/Miner/Packages/packages.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040223004512/http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/atari/Miner/Packages/packages.htm|title=Miner 2049er Packages|archivedate=February 23, 2004|accessdate=June 15, 2023}}</ref>

Joaquin Boaz said in ''[[InfoWorld]]'' that ''Miner 2049er'' was "selling like crazy".{{sfn|Boaz|1983|p=20}} ''[[Computer Entertainer]]'' reported that the ColecoVision version of the game by Micro Fun was the number-one-selling video game of the year.<ref name="1983Awards">{{cite magazine|title=Computer Entertainer â€“ Master Index/Awards|year=1989|page=14|magazine=Computer Entertainer/The Video Game Update}}</ref> In ''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]''{{'}}s [[Arkie Awards]] from January 1984, the game was described as "the most widely played home electronic game of all time", and the article also said that "no home-arcade title has had the impact" that the game had had to date.{{sfn|Kunkel|Katz|1984}} In a 2007 interview, Hogue reflected on the popularity of the game, saying that it was "a simple game and it's clear at first glance what needs to be done to finish a level. But as you're playing along you discover it wasn't quite as easy as you thought."{{sfn|Weiss|2014|p=139}}

In 2001,{{efn|The first version of the emulator, published in 2001, contains the "20010720" timestamp on its "Help/About..." window.<ref name="big5emu2001">{{cite web |last=Hogue |first=Bill |title=Big Five Software - Emulator |website=Big Five Software |url=http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/Emulator/emulator.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010909140838/http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/Emulator/emulator.htm |archive-date=9 September 2001}}</ref>}} Hogue released the game and its sequel, ''Bounty Bob Strikes Back!'', for free online with an embedded Atari 8-bit computer emulator.{{sfn|Grannell|2007|p=39}}<ref name="big5emu2007">{{cite web |last=Hogue |first=Bill |title=Big Five Software - Emulator |website=Big Five Software |date=18 January 2007 |orig-date=First published in 2001 |url=http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/Emulator/emulator.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914002339/http://www.bigfivesoftware.com/Emulator/emulator.htm |archive-date=14 September 2019}}</ref> Hogue said that he released it this way, as opposed to releasing the games' ROMs, as "I'd spent so much time back in the Eighties tweaking those color registers to achieve perfection and I wanted to see the game that way again."{{sfn|Grannell|2007|p=39}} [[Magmic]] released the game for mobile devices in 2007.{{sfn|Buchanan|2007}} The mobile version of the game featured a new, contemporary version of the game as well as the original, which was coded from scratch.{{sfn|Grannell|2007|p=39}} Both the Atari 800 and Atari 2600 versions of ''Miner2049er'' were included as part of the ''[[Atari 50|Atari 50: The Anniversary Celebration]]'' (2022) compilation for [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Steam (service)|Steam]], and [[Xbox One]].{{sfn|Machkovech|2022}}

