[[Tom Hudson (programmer)|Tom Hudson]] in ''[[ANALOG Computing]]'' had trouble believing that the game fit on a 16K cartridge and said that it was "one of those rare games which looks as if it were designed, not just thrown together." He noted that the mine and Bob weren't "just one-color graphics, but detailed multicolor objects" and that "the game itself was not abandoned in favor of graphics".{{sfn|Hudson|1982|p=14}} Boaz declared the game to be a "gourmet's delight that offers many, many levels of challenge" and applied "skillful use of colors" with its randomly generated palettes that broke up the monotony.{{sfn|Boaz|1983|p=20}} A reviewer credited as "MTY" in the magazine ''[[Softalk|Softline]]'' found that despite being similar to ''Donkey Kong'', ''[[Pac-Man]]'', and ''[[Apple Panic]]'', the game was original and that "unlike many arcade games, ''Miner'' doesn't require you to get faster as the pace picks up in order to attain the next level. It requires you to develop the different skills needed to survive."{{sfn|MTY|1983|p=36}}

''Computer Entertainer'' declared Bill Hogue the designer of the year in their 1983 awards listing.<ref name="1983Awards" /> ''Miner 2049er'' was awarded "1984 Electronic [[List of Game of the Year awards|Game of the Year]]" at the 5th annual [[Arkie Awards]].{{sfn|Kunkel|Katz|1984}} Scott Mace listed it as the "best arcade-type computer game" of 1983. ''InfoWorld'' praised its unique gameplay elements, action, and humor, saying that "you won't find anything like Miner in the arcades. That in itself is cause for celebration."  It noted that in a year of "endless adaptation of arcade games, some good, most bad", that the game {{"'}}out-donkey-kongs' ''[[Donkey Kong (arcade game)|Donkey Kong]]''".{{sfn|Mace|1983|p=55}} 

Reviewing the [[VIC-20]] version, [[Computer Entertainer|''The Video Game Update'']] found the game "addictive" with graphics that were "less than outstanding", but said that "there are enough challenges in this game to keep the player busy for many, many hours of frustration and triumph."<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update|volume=2|issue=2|date=May 1983|title=Critically Speaking. . . VIC 20}}</ref> The magazine also reviewed the Atari 2600 version, noting that the limitations of the Atari 2600 system meant that the graphics were "sacrificed somewhat" and the game was "considerably slower and less fluid than in the original computer game, but this version is still a very good game in its own right."<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=The Video Game Update|volume=2|issue=2|date=June 1983|title=Critically Speaking..Atari 2600-Compatible|page=34}}</ref> The publisher declared the Intellivision version to be the "best climbing game yet" for the system.<ref name="Atr481200" />

In retrospective reviews, ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' gave the Colecovision version an 82% rating in 1989, recommending it for fans of traditional platform games as one of the best on the system.<ref name="CVG">{{cite magazine |title=Complete Games Guide |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=October 16, 1989 |issue=Complete Guide to Consoles |page=61 |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/9/98/CompleteGuideToConsoles_UK_01.pdf|accessdate=June 10, 2023|location=United Kingdom}}</ref> Brett Alan Weiss reviewed the Atari 5200 version, declaring it "one of the best games of the early 1980s", noting that it was fast-paced, intricately designed, and a very long and diverse game. He said that unlike those in ''Donkey Kong'', pathways were not immediately obvious, and this made the game fun and more challenging.{{sfn|Weiss}} Levi Buchanan of [[IGN]] declared the mobile version to be "a pixel-perfect recreation of the original", finding the controls responsive for a mobile game.{{sfn|Buchanan|2007}} He found that the game was fun in 1984 and was also fun in 2007, and that the game merited a new audience. He recommended it for fans of games like ''Donkey Kong'' and ''[[BurgerTime]]''.{{sfn|Buchanan|2007}} The mobile version was later released for [[iOS]].{{sfn|Patterson|2011}}

==Legacy==
{{Quote box
|quote = Wonder if kids today think of ''Miner'' like we do. ''Miner'' returns us to a simpler time and perhaps that's why people like to play it again.
|source = â€” ''Miner 2049er'' programmer Bill Hogue in 2007{{sfn|Weiss|2014|p=139}}
|width = 40%
}}
Multiple games were directly influenced by ''Miner 2049er'', such as ''[[Manic Miner]]'', with its underground setting and oxygen levels measured with a timer.{{sfn|McAlpine|2019|p=50}} Matthew Smith, the creator of ''Manic Miner'' said that ''Miner 2049er'' was a major influence on his games and that Big Five Software made the best games on the Tandy.
{{sfn|Jones|2008|p=56}} A follow-up titled ''Scraper Caper'' was announced in 1983 but never released.<ref name="Atari50-2">{{cite video game |title=Atari 50 |developer=Digital Eclipse |publisher=Atari |date=November 11, 2022 |platform=Nintendo Switch |quote='''The Dawn of PCs: Miner 2049er''': Although it was touted in this November 1983 two-page advertisement spread, Bill Hogue's planned follow-up to Miner 2049er, called Scraper Caper, never actually came out. (Bounty Bob would make his return in a different game, called Bounty Bob Strikes Back!, in 1985.}}</ref> Hogue later claimed to have thrown away the disks and tapes containing ''Scraper Caper''.{{sfn|Weiss|2014|p=139}}

Livesay was working on a game for Micro Fun titled ''Miner 2049er II'', a title unrelated to ''Scraper Caper''. It was set to be released for the Apple II, [[Commodore 64]], Colecovision, and IBM PC.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Computer Entertainer|volume=3|issue=3|date=June 1984|title=Lotsa Fun at Micro Fun|page=36}}</ref> It was released for the [[Apple II]] in the fourth quarter of 1984.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=Computer Entertainer|volume=3|issue=10|date=January 1985|title=Availability Update|page=36}}</ref>

The next game in the series was ''[[Bounty Bob Strikes Back!]]'', released in 1985.<ref name="Atari50-2" /><ref name="Atari50-3">{{cite video game |title=Atari 50 |developer=Digital Eclipse |publisher=Atari |date=November 11, 2022 |platform=Nintendo Switch |quote='''The Dawn of PCs: Bounty Bob Strikes Back!''': Bill Hogue followed up Miner 2049er with Bounty Bob Strikes Back! While the gameplay was similar to the original, the graphics now had an appealing pseudo-3D look.}}</ref> Hogue stated that following the [[video game crash of 1983]] and the release of ''Bounty Bob Strikes Back!'', Big Five Software started scaling back their company operations until it was run out of Hogue's home; he eventually closed the company.{{sfn|Weiss|2014|p=35}}

Richard Stanton, in his book ''A Brief History of Video Games'' (2015), stated that ''Miner 2049er'' contributed to the popularity of [[platform game]]s on systems like the [[ZX Spectrum]].{{sfn|Stanton|2015|p=73}} [[Mindscape (company)|Mindscape]] released a version of the game for the [[Game Boy]] in the early 1990s. Hogue recalled that the Game Boy version was "a really poor sales performer".{{sfn|Grannell|2007|p=37}} Following the release of ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1985), Stanton said that ''Miner 2049er'' was "forgotten" and that Nintendo's game made it "look like a fossil".{{sfn|Stanton|2015|p=73}}

